>>>
…the real advantage of stateless replay is actually its resilience and transparency. With stateless replay, every request is self-contained, making it easy to recover from failures, audit, or debug issues—there’s no hidden state that can get out of sync or corrupted. Conversely, stateful sessions, while efficient, can hide subtle bugs or inconsistencies if session state is lost, corrupted, or mishandled, and recovering from such issues is much harder. So, stateless replay’s simplicity and robustness are often more valuable than the efficiency of stateful sessions, especially in distributed or fault-tolerant systems.
<<<

